children.subject: Personally I'm more EE than CS. I have not taken 160 before but I think it's more like a for senior only class because of the waitlist. If you want to explore more EE, I recommend EE105 or EE130. After that, you are pretty sure if you want to touch EE at all as an EECS major. (Plenty of EECS majors can't solder.) If you like math and signal stuff, EE120 is a great class to take if you consider yourself 'advanced' in your math ability. For CS side, I don't have much experience but I can at least speak about CS188, CS170, CS162 and EECS149. I don't think you should try CS188 and CS170 without knowledge in CS70. The pace of the classes is pretty fast so you better have a solid foundation. Take CS162 if you are ready for quite a lot of work and you like CS61C type material. If you want more coding training and a SW summer internship, take a coding part time job.

history.content: CS 160, CS 168 / EE 122, CS 169, CS 186, CS 162, CS 164 (lots of work)

The above student gave a pretty comprehensive list of courses that don't *require* EE16B or CS70, but I wanted to add that you may also want to avoid the heavier courses since you'd be taking 3 technicals in one term.  This would distill the list to CS160, 168, and 186.

What are some EECS upper division courses that I would be fine with taking EE16B and CS70 concurrently with? I know 16B and 70 are prereqs for many upper div EECS courses, so I'm kind of limited with what other EECS classes i can take.
history.subject: EECS upper divs
